			<h2 class="entry-title" itemprop="headline"><a href="https://survivalblog.com/preparedness-notes-friday-july-10-2020/"  itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" rel="bookmark">Preparedness Notes for Friday — July 10, 2020</a></h2>
			<div class="entry-meta aftertitle-meta">
				<span class="comments-link"><a href="https://survivalblog.com/preparedness-notes-friday-july-10-2020/#comments" itemprop="discussionURL"><i class="icon-comments icon-metas" title="2 Comments"></i><strong>2</strong></a></span>			</div><!-- .entry-meta -->

		</header><!-- .entry-header -->

		
				<div class="entry-content"  itemprop="articleBody">
					<p>July 10th is the birthday of British novelist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Wyndham" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">John Wyndham</a>. (His full name was John Wyndham Parkes Lucas Beynon Harris, but Harris shortened that to just John Wyndham for his pen name.) He we was born in 1903 and died March 11, 1969. Harris was a good friend of fellow novelist Samuel Youd (1922-2012), who wrote under several pen names, including John Christopher. Both men were famous for writing what are often called &#8220;cozy catastrophies&#8221;. Several of Wyndham&#8217;s novels and short stories have been adapted to film, with varying degrees of success. One of the best of these was a parallel universe story called <em><a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xg-Kqb88yeA" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">Random Quest</a></em>.</p>
<p>&#8212;</p>
